  1. Plot \(\sin(x)\) on the interval \(0 \le x \le 3\pi\). Label the axes with something meaningful.
t=seq(0,3*pi, 0.1)
y=sin(t)
plot(t,y,type="l", main = "Sin curve", xlab="unit", ylab="Sine wave")

  1. Plot both \(\sin(x)\) and \(\cos(x)\) for \(0 \le x \le 3\pi\) on the same axes. Use colors or line styles to distinguish the two curves. Include a figure legend that explains how to tell which curve is which.
plot(sin, 0, 3*pi, xlab="unit", ylab="Curve", col="red", main = "Sin-Cos curve")
curve(cos, 0, 3*pi, xlab="unit", col="blue", add=TRUE)
legend('topright',c("cos","sin"), lty=c(1,1), col=c("blue","red"), merge = TRUE)

  1. Generate two random normal vectors \(x\) and \(y\), each containing \(100\) elements.
    1. Compute the correlation coefficient between \(x\) and \(y\).
set.seed(124)
x<-rnorm(100)
set.seed(1)
y<-rnorm(100)
cor(x,y)
## [1] -0.03817069
b. Plot $y$ as a function of $x$, and add the correlation coefficient to the plot (as a legend, a label, or a text string). 
set.seed(124)
x<-rnorm(100)
set.seed(1)
y<-rnorm(100)
cor <- cor(x,y)
plot(x = x, y = y, xlab = "Vector x", ylab = "Vector y", main = "x as function of y")
text(x = -1, y = 1.6, labels = paste("Correlation:", cor, sep = " "), adj=0, col='red')

c. Perform a $t$-test comparing $x$ and $y$. What are the $t$-statistic and the $p$-value? 
set.seed(124)
x<-rnorm(100)
set.seed(1)
y<-rnorm(100)
t.test(x, y)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  x and y
## t = -0.78775, df = 197.95, p-value = 0.4318
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.3477678  0.1492341
## sample estimates:
##   mean of x   mean of y 
## 0.009620551 0.108887367

t-statistics is: -0.78775 and p-value is: 0.4318

e. Let $z=y+k$ for a constant $k$ of your choice. Repeat parts (5.a) and (5.c) using $z$ instead of $y$. How large should you choose $k$ to ensure that the $p$-value is smaller than 0.05?
set.seed(124)
x<-rnorm(100)
set.seed(1)
y<-rnorm(100)
z <- y+0.1498
cor(x,z)
## [1] -0.03817069
t.test(x, z)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  x and z
## t = -1.9765, df = 197.95, p-value = 0.04949
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.4975677757 -0.0005658554
## sample estimates:
##   mean of x   mean of y 
## 0.009620551 0.258687367

k should be approximately >0.15 so that the p-value is smaller than 0.05
